elements.content: The remarkable structural diversities arising from a small ligand, 2-amino,5-nitro-benzoic acid (L1H), equipped with different functional groups, conferring tunable coordination sites as well as H-bonding abilities, have been explored. Six new crystal structures of Cs­(I), Na­(I), K­(I), and Li­(I) ions with L1 have been realized. Notably, for the medium-sized alkali metal ions, a role reversal between the coordination and H-bonding nature of −COO– and −NO2 groups, respectively, has been observed for the first time. Since L1 possesses three potential sites for coordination as well as H-bonding interactions, we realized a delicate control of noncovalent interactions on the resulting supramolecular assemblies. Structural diversities observed range from one-dimensional helices and linear threads to two-dimensional brick-wall types or three-dimensional networks. The electrostatic surface potential (ESP) of three representative complexes provided an insight into the electronic-deficient and electron-rich regions. The coordination of Na­(I) and K­(I) ions through the nitro groups extends the electron-deficient region of the complexes. The electron densities at the bond critical paths of the representative complexes were calculated to understand the supramolecular outcome of the coordination polymers. Unravelling of such critical electronic information is paramount toward the systematic construction of a new generation of complex coordination polymers.

elements.content: The glue for the inorganic “crystal engineering” is the metal–ligand coordinate-covalent bond whose strength and directionality have been thoroughly exploited for engineering various molecular building blocks into diverse supramolecular architectures. It is well-known that the dimensionality of the resulting coordination networks can be increased by noncovalent interactions, like hydrogen bonds, π···π, C–H···π, halogen···halogen, aromatic ring···halogen, and other noncovalent interactions. Therefore, ligands/systems having more of such interacting groupsthe heterofunctional ligandsare a better bet for forming new architectures. The versatility of heterofunctional ligands to generate special structures, such as nanotubular skeletons, helical motifs, and isoreticular three-dimensional (3D) structures with tunable large cavities, is commendable but reported infrequently. For that reason, it is a good strategy to explore coordination polymers (CPs) using heterofunctional ligands. The ability of a charged ligand to form tunable H-bonds and modulate its coordination behavior in the presence of different metal ions can provide an effective tool-box to engineer new generations of CPs. It is therefore vital to discern the set of complex electronic information to have structural and temporal control over the assembly formation.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

The glue for the inorganic "crystal engineering" is the metal-ligand coordinate-covalent bond whose strength and directionality have been thoroughly exploited for engineering various molecular building blocks into diverse supramolecular architectures. It is well-known that the dimensionality of the resulting coordination networks can be increased by noncovalent interactions, like hydrogen bonds, π⋅⋅⋅π, C-H⋅⋅⋅π, halogen⋅⋅⋅halogen, aromatic ring⋅⋅⋅halogen, and other noncovalent interactions. Therefore, ligands/systems having more of such interacting groupsthe heterofunctional ligandsare a better bet for forming new architectures. The versatility of heterofunctional ligands to generate special structures, such as nanotubular skeletons, helical motifs, and isoreticular three-dimensional (3D) structures with tunable large cavities, is commendable but reported infrequently. For that reason, it is a good strategy to explore coordination polymers (CPs) using heterofunctional ligands. The ability of a charged ligand to form tunable H-bonds and modulate its coordination behavior in the presence of different metal ions can provide an effective tool-box to engineer new generations of CPs. It is therefore vital to discern the set of complex electronic information to have structural and temporal control over the assembly formation.

elements.content:
The heterofunctional molecule, 2-amino-5-nitrobenzoic acid (L1H), is one such system that got our attention for the following reasons:

It has a rigid backbone (aromatic) with given geometry and directionality, which makes it easy to control the desirable topologies.

More than one coordinating sites provided by −NH2, −NO2, and −COO– groups

Versatile coordination modes of the carboxylate groups in combination with −NO2 groups

Sensitivity to acid–base environment of carboxylate and −NH2 groups, which add to the structural diversity

Possible competition between coordination and H-bonds for the −COO– group owing to the presence of the −NH2 group ortho to it

Only four complexes (one with Ag­(I) and three with Sn­(IV) ions), based on CSD search, are known.

As all the different coordinating sites, −NH2, −NO2, and −COO–, are capable of forming strong H-bonds, the extension of CP due to H-bonding and other intermolecular interactions is envisaged. Metal nitrobenzoates are well-known to coordinate solely through the −COO– group, with H-bonding through −NO2 groups or show coordination both through −COO– and −NO2 groups. Therefore, while the formation of CPs owing to diverse coordination modes of −COO– groups is well expected, a possible competition between −COO– and −NO2 groups for the metal ions, leaving the other group mainly for H-bonding interactions, cannot be ruled out (). It is noteworthy here that, to the best of our knowledge, based upon a CSD search to date that no metal nitrobenzoate is known where −NO2 coordinates and −COO– participates in only H-bonding. Further with −NH2 presenting an additional H-bonding site, the outcome of the self-assembled product has to be highly dependent on a fine balance of these noncovalent interactions and their tuning by the metal ion.

elements.content: In continuation of our ongoing efforts to synthesize crystalline CPs with varied topologies, we report hereby single crystal X-ray structures of six complexes of alkali metal ions. For medium-sized alkali metal ions, a role reversal between the coordination and H-bonding nature of −COO– and −NO2 groups, respectively, has been observed. Structural diversities observed range from one-dimensional (1D) helices and linear threads to two-dimensional (2D) brick-wall type or 3D networks. Density functional theory calculations for electron density maps have been performed to supplement and rationalize the crystallographic results.

Experimental Section

Materials and Physical Measurements

All the reagents were commercially available and used as received. The melting points were determined with an electrically heated apparatus. C, H, N elemental analyses were obtained with a CHNS-O analyzer flash-EA-1112 series. The IR spectra of complexes were recorded on Perkin ELMER Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectrometer in the range 4000-400 cm-1. Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) data were collected on a NetzschTG-209 instrument. Single crystal structural X-ray diffraction was carried out on a Bruker's Apex-II CCD diffractometer using Mo Kα (λ = 0.71069 Å) at room temperature.

elements.content: The ground-state geometry optimization was carried out applying DFT with the Becke three-parameter hybrid exchange functional in concurrence with the Lee–Yang–Parr gradient-corrected correlation function (B3LYP functional) with the 6-311G++(d,p) basis set as implemented in Gaussian 09W. For finding the HOMO–LUMO energy levels, bulk solvent (H2O) effects were approximated by a polarizable continuum model (PCM), using single point energy calculations with B3LYP/6-31++G­(d,p). The electrostatic potentials (ESP) mapped on the electronic density surfaces based on the DFT calculations and plotted with the GaussView 5.0 program. Natural population analysis (NPA) were calculated using the same basis set. AIM calculations: For finding electron density at the bond critical path (BCP), the Multiwfn program has been applied. The input files (.wfx) were generated by DFT calculations with the same basis set in Gaussian 09W. The contour plots and interacting BCP points were visualized by this software.

Theoretical Calculations

The ground-state geometry optimization was carried out applying DFT with the Becke three-parameter hybrid exchange functional in concurrence with the Lee-Yang-Parr gradient-corrected correlation function (B3LYP functional) with the 6-311G++(d,p) basis set as implemented in Gaussian 09W. For finding the HOMO-LUMO energy levels, bulk solvent (H2O) effects were approximated by a polarizable continuum model (PCM), using single point energy calculations with B3LYP/6-31++G(d,p). The electrostatic potentials (ESP) mapped on the electronic density surfaces based on the DFT calculations and plotted with the GaussView 5.0 program. Natural population analysis (NPA) were calculated using the same basis set. AIM calculations: For finding electron density at the bond critical path (BCP), the Multiwfn program has been applied. The input files (.wfx) were generated by DFT calculations with the same basis set in Gaussian 09W. The contour plots and interacting BCP points were visualized by this software.

elements.content: X-ray data of all these complexes were collected on a Bruker’s Apex-II CCD diffractometer using Mo Kα (λ = 0.71069 Å) at room temperature. The data collected by CCD diffractometer were processed by SAINT correcting for Lorentz and polarization effects. An empirical absorption correction was applied using SADABS from Bruker. The structures were solved by direct methods, using SIR-92 and refined by full-matrix least-squares refinement methods based on F2, using SHELX-97. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. Phenylene hydrogen atoms were fixed geometrically with their U iso values 1.2 times of the carbons. Protons of carboxylic acid, water, amino group, and ammonium ion were located from the difference Fourier synthesis and were refined isotropically with constraints on their bond distances and with U iso values 1.2 times that of their carrier oxygen and nitrogen atoms, respectively. All calculations were performed using the Wingx package. Crystal data and structure refinements for complexes (I–VI) are given in . Important bond distances (Å) and bond angles (deg), and important H-bonding interactions in complexes (I–VI) are given in Tables TS1 and TS2, respectively.

Results and Discussion

Crystal Structures of Three-Dimensional Polymeric Complex

[Cs(L1)⋅(L1H)] n  (I)

Complex (I) is a 3D polymer, which is solved in monoclinic centrosymmetric space group C2/c. Its asymmetric unit contains half Cs(I) ion and one L1 anion. Since Cs(I) is at the 2-fold axis of rotation, the located H2A oxygen of the carboxylic oxygen O2 has been assigned a site occupancy of half (one H between two L1 anions; disordered about the 2-fold axis) to account for the overall charge of the complex (Figure S1). The Cs(I) ion is decacoordinated (a) having a distorted bicapped square antiprismatic geometry. In this complex, oxygen atoms of nitro groups and nitrogen atoms of amino groups also coordinate along with the carboxylate oxygen atoms. Cs(I) is coordinated with O1 and O2 atoms of carboxylate group with distances of 3.355(2) and 3.392(2) Å, respectively, O3, and O4 atoms of nitro groups with distances of 3.172(2) and 3.288(2) Å, respectively, and the N1 atom of amine group with a distance 3.534(3) Å.

elements.content: The coordination mode of L1 in this complex is (μ5-κ5, η1:η1:η1:η1:η1, (i)), while the complex is a 3D coordinated polymer as shown in ac and ab planes (b,c). Topologically, the structure consists of an eight-connected uninodal net where the point symbol for Cs1 and net is (36.416.56) with type tsi;8/3/t1;sqc106 (d). The 3D CP is further strengthened by π···π interactions between two aromatic rings with distance 3.717 Å as shown in the ac plane (e). Intramolecular H-bonding interactions between carboxylate oxygen O2 and −NH2 group (N1-(H1A)···O2 = 2.678(5) Å, Table TS2) are seen, which is a common feature in all the complexes. Through H1A, the amine forms a bifurcated intermolecular H-bond to nitro oxygen O4. The amine group also forms an intermolecular H-bond with −COO oxygen O2. Since H2A is a disordered proton about the 2-fold axis, O2···H2A···H2A···O2 = 2.43 Å is akin to a quasi-covalent H-bond in an acid salt pair.

Crystal Structure of 1D Polymeric Complexes

[Na(L1)⋅(H2O)2] n  (II)

Complex (II) is a 1D polymer, solved in monoclinic centrosymmetric space group P21/n. Its asymmetric unit contains one Na(I) ion, one L1 anion, and two coordinated water molecules (Figure S2). The Na(I) ion is seven coordinated having a monocapped distorted octahedral geometry (a). The polymeric complex is unique because the nitro group is coordinating with the metal ion instead of the carboxylate (b). Two water molecules O1W and O2W are forming bridges between two Na(I) ions.

elements.content: In the molecular structure of the complex, one Na metal ion is coordinated to two L1 anions through oxygen atom O3 and O4 of nitro groups (b), following a coordination mode of L1 as (μ2-κ3,η2:η1), in syn, syn conformation, forming 1D undulating chains along the b axis with Na···Na distance of 3.599(2) Å (c). Topologically, the 2C1 type, 1D CP consists of [0 1 0] chains with 2-c uninodal net (d). This 1D chain is supported by intra- and intermolecular H-bonding interactions between amino and carboxylate oxygens O2 and O1, respectively. A strong H-bonding between the carboxylate group and the bridging water molecules extends this 1D CP into an overall 3D coordination-cum-H-bonded network in the ac plane (e) Viewed down the b axis, the 1D CPs are arranged in stacks connecting to each other through −COO and water H-bonding, forming supramolecular synthons R 2 2 (20) and R 4 2 (8) (f). Both these synthons result from carboxylate-water H-bonding (g), but they are formed by an association between two and four 1D CPs, respectively. This 2D H-bonded network is further supported by offset π···π (centroid···centroid distance = 3.952 Å) between two adjacent phenyl rings (e).

As all the complexes of L1 are expected to explode at a certain temperature, but this temperature has been seen to vary in different complexes. The thermal stability of complexes may be related to dimensionality and architecture of the complex. Three-dimensional polymeric complex (I) has high thermal stability and decomposes at a high temperature, which is >410 °C, while 1D polymeric complexes ((II) to (IV)) decompose in the range of 236–390 °C. elements.content: Further, Li­(I) complexes (V) (1D CP) and (VI) ( an ionic complex), are good examples of the “Gulliver effect” when a small number of stronger coordination bonds are taken over by a large number of weaker H-bonding interactions. In (V), one oxygen atom of carboxylate group is having one coordinate and one hydrogen bond, while −NO2 group has three H-bonds with water and −NH2 groups. In (VI), there is no coordinate bond to Li with carboxylate oxygens but the latter are involved in forming ten H-bonds with water, −NH2 and NH4 + and −NO2 groups have four H-bonds with water and NH4 +. Besides these, there are two water···water and three water···NH4 + interactions. Thus, though both the complexes have four coordination bonds each (Li-L1 and Li-water in (V) and Li-water in (VI)) but total number of H-bonds is four in (V) and 19 in (VI). Thus, high hydration energy of Li­(I) ions in the basic solution, has facilitated the weaker noncovalent interactions to turn the tables in their favor instead of coordinate bonding with the carboxylate group.

We have restricted all our calculations to three representative complexes (II, III, and V). ESP maps clearly exhibited a gradual transition of the central electron-rich region in the Li complex (V) to the electron-deficient region in the Na complex (II) and highly electron-deficient region in the K complex (III) (). The Na­(I) and K­(I) ion complexation through the nitro groups considerably extends the electron-deficient region in the complexes beyond the central region, and this aspect is demonstrated clearly in the aqueous phase.

We have restricted all our calculations to three representative complexes (II, III, and V). elements.content: The HOMO and LUMO energies of the complexes decreased on going from the complex (V) to (II) and (III) (Table TS5). The decrease in the LUMO energy levels is more pronounced as the chelation is initiated through the electron withdrawing nitro groups in complexes (II) and (III). The overall hardness of (V) was then determined to be 1.74, while for (II) and (III) it was considerably lower at 1.272 and 1.148, respectively, in the aqueous phase. This clearly showed that the Li­(I) ion complexes are significantly harder, and with increasing size of the metal ion and diffused electron density the hardness decreases in the Na­(I) and K­(I) ion complexes. The change in the FMO energies and the η values nicely reflects the built-in ability of the ligand to switch its chelation through the carboxylate or the nitro group depending on the size and electron density of the metal ions.

elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

Since a detailed study of various noncovalent interactions shaping the final outcome of a self-assembly process is the very soul of crystal engineering, a delicate balance between the noncovalent interactions, i.e., the coordinate bonds vs all other interelectronic interactions has been observed and studied under its realm. Strength, directionality, and distance dependence of these intermolecular interactions not only dictate the primary structure, but they also guide the secondary structure. A huge difference between the strength of covalent coordinate bond (mostly 75-125 kcal/mol) and H-bond (usually less than 4-40 kcal/mol) has been compensated and overridden by involving a large number of the latter. The change in the FMO energies and the η values nicely reflects the built-in ability of the ligand to switch its chelation through the carboxylate or the nitro group depending on the size and electron density of the metal ions. Electron density ρ at the BCP, for M-O interactions, ranges from 0.04096 to 0.00286 a.u., which is the range of ρ values of neutral hydrogen bonds (ρH-bond ~ 0.002-0.04 au), suggesting that the M-O interaction energy is comparable with the H-bonds. Importantly, M-O interaction energy decreases on going from complex Li to Na to K, which indicates that the Li+ ion makes a stronger interaction with the ligand through the carboxylate group as well as water molecules compared to the Na+ and K+ ions.
